65 Since Vergil’s object was to praise the whole glorious career of Rome (ὅ 61) it was inevitable that he should dwell with especial emphasis on the age of Augustus, an age which to¹ many must have seemed the brightest epoch in that career. In the twelve years between the battle of Actium and the death of Vergil Italy and the provinces had abundantly ex- perienced the benefits of the rule of Augustus(§§16,17). When we remcmber that for a hundred years civil war, with its attendant horrors of bloodshed and proscriptione, had been almost incessant, we can readily forgive Vergil and his contemporaries for characterizing as more than human the man through whose masterful rule war had been replaced by peace, and chaos by law and order.
